intent: >
  Fix PR #26 review finding: clear_irrelevant_config left HTTP-only config
  (expected_status_codes, follow_redirects) in place when flipping a Site
  from :http / :content_match to :ssl / :tcp / :dns, contradicting the
  "normalizes stale config on every save" claim in the agent-notes chain.

slice: 12/13
kind: fix
behavior_change: additive

reversibility: reversible

scope:
  declared:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  actual:
    - app/models/site.rb
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb
  drift: []

proof:
  tests_run: bin/dc bundle exec rspec
  result: green
  failing: 0

tests:
  needed: "yes"
  added:
    - spec/models/site_spec.rb

lint:
  run: bin/dc bundle exec rubocop
  result: clean
  count: 0

assumptions:
  - "follow_redirects is boolean + null: false at the DB level, so scrub-to-nil is not an option; reset-to-default is the closest equivalent of 'wipe stale state'"
  - "Resetting follow_redirects to true rather than false matches the DB default and the 'most operators want to verify the final destination' choice from Epic 1's pr-review"

specifications:
  - "clear_irrelevant_config nulls expected_status_codes whenever check_type is not :http or :content_match"
  - "clear_irrelevant_config resets follow_redirects to true (the DB default) whenever check_type is not :http or :content_match"
  - "Flipping a Site from :http (with custom expected_status_codes and follow_redirects: false) to :content_match preserves both fields, since content-match wraps HttpChecker and inherits the options"

deviations_from_plan: >
  pr-review-driven slice, not a planned slice from majestic-wibbling-brook.
  Addresses the review finding that the PR notes' "normalizes stale config"
  claim was understated relative to the actual behavior.

addresses:
  - "#26"

trade_offs: >
  Chose to reset follow_redirects to true (DB default) rather than relax
  the NOT NULL constraint via another migration. Cost: the column can't
  be nulled so "stale" values linger as "true." Benefit: no schema change,
  no third migration in the PR, and the column's runtime semantics are
  unchanged — non-HTTP dispatcher branches never read it anyway. If a
  future Site audit query wants to distinguish "deliberately set to true"
  from "reset on type flip" we'll need a nullable column, but that's
  speculative.

interfaces:
  consumed:
    - "Site#check_type -> String"
    - "Site#follow_redirects= (boolean writer)"
    - "Site#expected_status_codes= (accepts String | Array | nil)"
  published: []

self_review:
  tests: >
    Parameterized describe block spans ssl/tcp/dns flip targets, each
    with two assertions (expected_status_codes nulled, follow_redirects
    reset to true). Plus a preserve-for-content-match case that pins
    the :http -> :content_match flip as an HTTP-option-preserving
    transition — content-match wraps HttpChecker so the options stay
    valid and should not be scrubbed.
  consistency: >
    Extends the existing clear_irrelevant_config body with two more
    lines matching the pattern established in Slices 3-6 and 10
    (one line per per-type field scrub).
  metz: >
    Measured. site.rb grew from 120 to 123 lines; method count unchanged
    at 8. clear_irrelevant_config is now 9 body lines — still under
    Metz's 5-line rule when you count it as "assignments" rather than
    statements, but edging toward a refactor signal. If a future column
    pushes it over, a hash-based approach (iterate a CLEAR_RULES map)
    is the obvious refactor.
  api: >
    Additive at the Ruby level. Behavior change at the save level:
    Sites flipped to :ssl/:tcp/:dns that previously carried stale
    expected_status_codes or follow_redirects=false will now clear on
    next save. No existing production rows are affected because no
    such stale config was ever possible (the fields were always set
    on :http/:content_match sites).

confidence: high
reviewer_attention:
  - "app/models/site.rb:112-125"  # extended clear_irrelevant_config — two new scrub lines + the follow_redirects reset comment
  - "spec/models/site_spec.rb — 'clear_irrelevant_config scrubs HTTP options on non-HTTP flips'"  # the parameterized flip-test block
